<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=6597&amp;p=67305#p67305"><![CDATA[
That's interesting how it does interrupts. Reminds me of how most mechanisms in biological systems work, where one thing is re-used to do something else similar, because it uses less wetware. The 6502 is very much like this all over, as I understand it, and was one reason it was so thrifty on transistors in comparison to other processors at the time. Was the reason for the so-called hardware bugs, for example JMP ($01FF) or LDA $FF,X where X is non-zero, which were really intentional tradeoffs made to reduce cycle count of instructions and use less hardware.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=17">blargg</a> — Mon Sep 06, 2010 11:13 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
