<id>http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=6597&amp;p=67303#p67303</id>
<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=6597&amp;p=67303#p67303"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[A little help with Blargg's nes_instr_test?]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=6597&amp;p=67303#p67303"><![CDATA[
<div class="quotetitle">blargg wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><br />The byte on the stack that holds the status flags also holds a flag indicating whether it was a BRK or IRQ.<br /></div><br />Yes, this is putting it quite nicely. SOMETHING gets pushed to stack, but it's not a Flag in the same sense as Carry, for instance. It is the signal called D1x1 on that big schematic. There is no provision (or need) for software to set, clear or restore D1x1.<br /><br />We're discussing this matter in <a href="http://forum.6502.org/viewtopic.php?t=1634&amp;postdays=0&amp;postorder=asc&amp;start=0" class="postlink">a thread</a> over on 6502.org. We start on a closely related topic and end up discussing <strong>nitty gritty details of interrupts</strong> (including BRK), at the schematic level.<br /><br />As for D1x1, maybe I shouldn't try to summarize this, but here goes. If I botch the summary you can still refer to the actual discussion!  <img src="http://forums.nesdev.com/images/smilies/icon_rolleyes.gif" alt=":roll:" title="Rolling Eyes" /> <br /><br />A 6502 hardware interrupt works by forcing the Instruction Register to all zeroes: ie, the BRK opcode. But BRK invoked in this fashion (IRQ, NMI) needs to execute slightly differently than the software version of BRK that we're already familiar with. D1x1 is what causes the difference; ie, it distinguishes $00 caused by software from $00 caused by hardware. D1x1 comes from a flip-flop that's set throughout the instruction cycle during which a hardware-induced BRK (ie, interrupt) executes. It is also the bit (yes, bit 4!!) that gets pushed to the stack in the Flags byte.<br /><br /> Maybe this will help shed some light. If it simply duplicates info already present here on NESDEV then I apologize; I'm a new member here.<br /><br />regards to all you 6502 fellows,<br /><br /> Jeff<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=4558">Dr Jefyll</a> — Mon Sep 06, 2010 8:56 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
