Hopefully you don't have to make a video to prove it. I don't see how anyone could doubt this behavior. It's documented, and it's what BRK is for. If you had lots of system calls in a program, BRK could reduce its size considerably. Maybe some scripting system or something. And of course there's the use on PROM where you can always set a byte to zero. I believe some NES games use BRK as well.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=17">blargg</a> — Wed Jul 14, 2010 7:31 pm</p><hr />
